    ```javascript
function numOfArrays(n, maxValue) {
    const mod = 1e9 + 7;
    const dp = Array(maxValue + 1).fill(0);

    for (let i = 1; i <= maxValue; i++) {
        dp[i] = i;
    }

    for (let i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        for (let j = maxValue; j > 0; j--) {
            dp[j] = (dp[j] + dp[j - 1]) % mod;
        }
    }

    return dp[maxValue];
}
```


    The problem can be solved using dynamic programming, where we maintain an array `dp` of length `maxValue + 1`.

1. Initialize the `dp` array by assigning `i` to `dp[i]` for `i` in the range `[1, maxValue]`.
2. We need to find the number of ideal arrays of length `n`. So, we iterate from `1` to `n - 1`. In each iteration, we update the `dp` array.
3. For updating the `dp` array, we iterate from `maxValue` to `1`, and we update `dp[j]` as `(dp[j] + dp[j - 1]) % mod`, where `mod` is `10^9 + 7`.
4. The result of the function is the value at `dp[maxValue]`.

The time complexity of this algorithm is O(n * maxValue) and the space complexity is O(maxValue).

